<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence from Dr Michael Gordon, Lecturer in Law</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Dr Michael Gordon, Lecturer in Law</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Liverpool Law School, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">University of Liverpool (CRJ 07)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">This submission is a response to the Political and Constitutional Reform Committee’s call for evidence into the potential constitutional role of the judiciary in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">the event that the constitution of the UK were to be codified.  It will focus</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> in particular on</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> the Committee’s question 3:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">If the UK were to have a codified constitution, what powers should the courts have if they held that a piece of leg</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">islation was unconstitutional? (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">a) What would be the implications of these powers on existing constitutional do</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ctrines, including parliamentary sovereignty and judicial review?</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The potential constitutional role of the judiciary</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> is a topic which the committee is right to consider worthy of attention in its own right, as part of its ongoing attempts to explore and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">map the path to codification in the UK, if such a process were ever to be undertaken.  The significance of the issue is due to the fact that, for many, the codification of the UK constitution would of necessity imply a particular role for the judiciary.  T</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">hat is, that a judiciary operating within a codified constitutional system would inevitably have an active role in the enforcement of fundamental constitutional norms, both in conflicts between other institutions (or levels) of government, and in clashes b</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">etween citizens and the state.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Such assumptions, however, require close scrutiny.  In particular, this submission will focus on the impact that such a view of codification would have on the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty.  While it may be thought t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">hat this doctrine could have no place in a codified UK constitution, I will suggest that this is not the case.  Indeed, a codified constitution could be crafted which retains the sovereignty of Parliament (or at least, a legal state of affairs which is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ess</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">entially</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> equivalent to the present position), and further, the value of this doctrine would be an important factor to consider as part of any pre-codification debate about the desirability of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">allocating to the judiciary a more active constitutional role.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Parliamentary sovereignty in a codified constitution</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The present status of the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty is the subject of vibrant constitutional debate in the UK.  Developments such as the UK’s membership of the EU, and the domestic supremacy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> of EU norms which is a consequence of that membership, the enactment of the Human Rights Act 1998, and the modern devolution of legislative power to Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland can ostensibly be seen to challenge the traditional Diceyan notion th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">at Parliament can make or unmake any law whatever, with no body or institution empowered to reject Acts of the UK legislature.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  In particular, the fact that the UK courts are now required to assess the compatibility of Acts of Parliament with EU law and EC</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">HR rights, disapplying legislation which violates the former,</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">making a declaration of the incompatibility where appropriate in relation to the latter,</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> is clear evidence that the constitutional role of the courts has developed considerably since Dicey’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">s account of Parliament’s sovereignty was formulated.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Yet such developments must also be recognised to be a consequence of Parliament’s sovereignty.  The courts may now review legislation, but only because they have been instructed to do so by Parliament.  There has been recent discussion of whether the court</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">s might attempt to establish a free-standing common law power to review the legality of Acts of Parliament, a matter which received support in the obiter dicta of a minority of judges in a case before the House of Lords in 2004.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  While there exists no con</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">sensus as to whether the judicial creation of such a power would be desirable, any attempt to do so would be highly controversial, and of dubious legali</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ty; it would certainly constitute a direct challenge to the sovereignty of Parlia</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ment, the continuing im</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">portance of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">which Parliament has recently </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">sought to reiterate in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">legislation.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Yet, accepting that parliamentary sovereignty remains the fundamental doctrine of UK constitutional law, could this position be sustained if the constitution were to be codifie</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">d?  It might see</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">m that this would be impossible;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> that codification would replace the sovereignty of Parliament with something like the sovereignty of the constitution.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  Authority would be understood to flow from the constitutional text itself, and Parliam</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ent would be subject to the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">just </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">as all other state institutions.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The courts would therefore of necessity be required to ensure that Parliament, just as all other state institutions, operated only within its constitutional powers, with full c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">onstitutional review of legislation needed to guarantee the legality of legislation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The view outlined above – that codification of the UK constitution would inevitably displace the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty, with full powers of constitutional</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> review allocated to the courts – may appear plausible, but is ultimately mistaken.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">At its core, parliamentary sovereignty is a doctrine which allocates legally unlimited legislative power to Parliament.  This substantively unlimited law-making authority </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">must nevertheless be exercised in accordance with a procedure prescribed by law.  For an Act of Parliament to be created, a Bill must be assented to by the Queen, the House of Commons and the House of Lords (unless the provisions of the Parliament Acts 191</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">1 and 1949 are satisfied).  If the UK constitution were to be codified, the legal rules setting out the procedure by which Parliament can legislate would of course take a different </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">form</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, as</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> they would be contained in a constitutional text or instrument.  B</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ut there is no reason that they would need to change in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">substance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">; the codified constitution could simply prescribe that whatever the Queen-in-Parliament enacts is law.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">It is therefore clear that there could be a place for what we presently understand to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">be the sovereignty of Parliament within a future codified UK constitution.  The substance of the doctrine may need to be disaggregated from its present constitutional form; it may </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">no longer be appropriate to talk of the ‘sovereignty’ of Parliament if its l</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">egislative authority is seen to derive from a codified constitutional instrument.  While this is not inevitable – it would certainly be possible for a codified constitution to recognise explicitly the ‘sovereignty of Parliament’ – the underlying notion of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">legally unlimited legislative power could readily be retained even if the existing terminology was not.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The retention of something like the sovereignty of Parliament within a future codified UK constitution would of course have important implications for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">the very status of that constitution.  In principle, the constitution would be open to amendment by simple Act of Parliament, rather than entrenched and subject to modification only in accordance with a special procedure of some variety.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  This may appear u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">nusual in comparison with most codified constitutions adopted in states around the world.  Yet it would also reflect the flexible approach to constitutional reform traditionally adhered to in the UK, whereby even the most fundamental change to the constitu</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">tion can be effected by Act of Parliament.  Furthermore, there would perhaps be scope for constitutional conventions to emerge in relation to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Parliament</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">s power to effect fundamental ch</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ange to a codified constitution,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> for example, requiring such change to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">be put to the electorate at a referendum, complementing existing rules internal to Parliament as to how constitutional </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ills must be dealt with.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">It might even be open to consider whether a ‘manner and form’ understanding of parliamentary sovereignty – wh</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ich holds that Parliament has the power to alter the law-making process by legislation</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> – could permit different legislative procedures to be adopted for different legislative purposes without undermining Parliament’s claim to possess law-making authority </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">hich is substantively unlimited by a codified constitution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Power of the courts in a codified constitution</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">That a codified constitution could be adopted which allocated legally unlimited legislative power to Parliament demonstrates that there is nothing</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> inevitable about the constitutional role which the courts would perform were such a step to be taken in the UK.  The content of a codified constitution could be tailored to give the courts a limited role, a more expansive role, or some position in between</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  Whether the courts should even possess the power to hold legislation unconstitutional, and if so, what the consequences of such a determination might be, would thus need to be the subject of careful</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, and wide-ranging,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> deliberation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Views will doubtless</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ly vary as to the desirability of allocating to the courts a power to review the constitutionality of legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> under a codified constitution, whether the making of such a determination had concrete legal consequences (as at present in relation to disapp</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">lication of legislation violating EU law) or not (as would be comparable to the declarations of incompatibility presently available under the Human Rights Act 1998). </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">For defenders of the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty, the fact that it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">operates to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">prevent the development by </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">courts of a free-standing jurisdiction to review, and potentially pronounce on the legality of, Acts of Parliament, is an important part of its value.  For it can be understood to be desirable as a matter of democratic princi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ple for elected, representative and accountable Members of Parliament to have the final say in relation to the contested political questions that must be sett</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">led in a state, rather than members of the senior judiciary.  As part of any codification exercise</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, such arguments would need to be carefully considered, alongside the counter-arguments suggesting that the courts ought to have a role in assessing the constitutionality of legislation, perhaps in order to protect fundamental </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">values or rights, or to ensur</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">e that other institutions of government did not exceed their allocated powers (perhaps especially important if the future codified UK constitution were to adopt some sort of federal distribution of power between central government and the constituent natio</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ns or regions).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Yet</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> having such broad debates about the desirability of organising a constitution around the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty, or the underlying notion of legally unlimited legislative power, is the way that a codification exercise </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">would have to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> proceed.  It cannot be assumed that the sovereignty of Parliament will inevitably be displaced by a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">codified constitution.  My own view is that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">this</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> is a doctrine that should not be dispensed with even in the event of codification of the UK c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">onstitution.  But </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">there will be disagreement about this, and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">how the relationship between the courts and the legislature ought to be constituted will be one of the key issues</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> to be discussed if such structural change to the UK constitution were ever under</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">consideration</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">; indeed, the opportunity to have such </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">public </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">debates would be one of the principal attractions of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">a codification exercise.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  Ultimately,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> the impact of codification on the powers of the courts in relation to the constitutionality of legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, and the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">cannot be settled in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">advance, and in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">the abstract.  Instead, how the existing relationship between Parliament and the courts </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">would be</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> altered (if at all), </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">would depend on the content of the codified constitu</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">tion we chose to adopt.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">1 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> European Communities Act 1972</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, s.2(4)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> v. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Secretary of State for Transport, ex p. Factortame (No. 2)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> [1991] 1 A.C. 603</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Human Rights Act</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, s.4.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">. (Jackson)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> v</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Attorney General</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> [2005] UKHL 56; [2006] 1 A.C. 262</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">European Union Act 2011, s.18.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> See e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">discussion of these issues in Sir John Laws, ‘Law and Democracy’ [1995] </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Public Law</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> 72-93. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> E.g. constitutional bills </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">subject</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> to scrutiny at</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> committee stage by a Committee of the Whole House.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> See e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">W.I. Jennings, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The Law and the Constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (London: University of London Press, 5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> ed. 1959).</span></p></body></html>